+
+## C. DICTION FINGERPRINT
+
+**Word Length Tendency:** Middle register tending short. Anglo-Saxon vocabulary dominates: "little," "great," "big," "said," "went," "came." Latinate words appear in the politeness register ("presently," "certainly," "therefore") but not for description or action.
+
+**Vocabulary Clusters:**
+- Scale: little, great, big, tiny, enormous, beautiful, splendid, magnificent
+- Politeness: quite, rather, indeed, perhaps, certainly, surely, presently, therefore, afterward
+- Morality: wicked, kind, kindly, brave, courage, bold
+- Geography: country, journey, road, path, forest, city, land, kingdom
+- Observation: curious, strange, queer, wonderful, remarkable
+- Emotion: glad, happy, pleased, delighted, afraid, frightened
+
+**Register:** Late-Victorian children's literature. Formal without being academic. Courteous without being ornate. A storyteller speaking to children from a comfortable armchair, not a professor lecturing from a podium.
+
+**Formality:** Elevated-conversational. The narrator uses formal connectors ("therefore," "presently," "afterward") but frames them within conversational direct address ("you see," "you know," "of course"). Characters speak with grammatical courtesy regardless of social station.
+
+**Overused (Signature):**
+
+| Word | Count | Per 1k | Function |
+|------|-------|--------|----------|
+| little | 606 | 2.87 | Default diminutive for everything |
+| great | 339 | 1.60 | Default amplifier |
+| big | 207 | 0.98 | Secondary size marker |
+| quite | 149 | 0.70 | Politeness hedge / intensifier |
+| indeed | 102 | 0.48 | Confirmation / emphasis |
+| beautiful | 142 | 0.67 | Primary aesthetic descriptor |
+| rather | 70 | 0.33 | Qualification / understatement |
+| perhaps | 82 | 0.39 | Epistemic politeness |
+| certainly | 47 | 0.22 | Confident assertion |
+| surely | 41 | 0.19 | Expectation marker |
+| presently | 29 | 0.14 | Temporal transition (= soon) |
+| dreadful | 50 | 0.24 | Intensified negative |
+| splendid | 40 | 0.19 | Intensified positive |
+| queer | 55 | 0.26 | = strange/unusual (period usage) |
+| creature | 59 | 0.28 | Generic being descriptor |
+| country | 209 | 0.99 | Geographic unit of Oz |
+| journey | 88 | 0.42 | Travel narrative marker |
+| afterward | 45 | 0.21 | Temporal connector |
+| therefore | 43 | 0.20 | Logical connector |
+
+**Avoided:** Modern analytic vocabulary (analyze, assess, evaluate, process, scenario, situation). Sentimental vocabulary (heart swelling, tears of joy). Philosophical abstraction (meaning, truth, existence). Modern casual intensifiers (literally, basically, totally, absolutely, definitely, awesome, incredible). Slang of any era.
+
+**Adverb Profile (16.8/1k words):**
+Baum uses adverbs liberally -- 16.8/1k words, well above modern convention. This is a feature, not a bug. Top adverbs by frequency: "only" (244), "quickly" (65+), "carefully" (62+), "really" (91), "greatly" (50+), "suddenly" (48+), "surely" (41), "presently" (29), "eagerly" (30+), "thoughtfully" (25+). Adverbs in Baum's prose are specific and physical -- they describe how actions are performed, not how characters feel internally. This is Victorian craft, not modern adverb-bloat.
+
